===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Bronze inscriptions: {{Han compound|貝|𠂈|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=cowrie; shell|tr2=*tˤiŋ|tr=*tiŋ}}. {{zh-l|𠂈}} is the original pictograph of {{och-l|顛|tr=*tˤiŋ}} (“to fall headlong”).<ref>謝明文：《釋“顛”字》</ref><ref>蔣玉斌：《釋殷墟花東卜辭的“顛”》</ref> From the late Western Zhou period, forms with {{zh-l|鼎}} instead of {{zh-l|*貝}} are also attested.

Oracle-bone forms are composed of {{zh-l|匕}} (“spoon”) and {{zh-l|鼎}}. These have been read by some scholars as {{zh-l|真}}<ref>陳年福：《實用甲骨文字典》，四川辭書出版社，2019年。</ref>, but some of them are better interpreted as {{zh-l|肆}}<ref>陳劍：《甲骨金文舊釋“䵼”之字及相關諸字新釋》，《出土文獻與古文字研究》第二輯，上海：復旦大學出版社，2008年，第13–47頁。</ref> or {{zh-l|煮}}<ref>王子楊：《甲骨文煮字補釋》，《出土文獻研究》第十八輯，上海：中西書局，2019年，第22–35頁。</ref>.

In Chu bamboo-slip script, forms with {{zh-l|鼎}} became dominant. The legs of {{zh-l|鼎}} gradually became graphically confused with {{zh-l|火}}, and the lower horizontal stroke, left-falling stroke, and dot in Qin-slip and later forms of {{zh-l|真}} may be reduced from {{zh-l|火}}. In the Zeng Hou Yi bamboo slips, an elaborated form with an added {{zh-l|丌}} at the bottom is also attested.

===Etymology===
From {{der|zh|sit-pro|-}}; cognate with {{cog|bo|བདེན||true; truth}}. Possibly connected with {{och-l|貞}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

